When calling this method, you are telling WebDriver to wait until the WebElement&#39;s `style` attribute value is equal to `display: none;` meaning the loader is no longer visible.

Selenium has `ExpectedConditions` built in that you can use with `WebDriverWait` to handle situations like this. It might be the case that your wait for invisible is firing and passing before the loader becomes visible which could cause later actions to fail because the loader appears later. You might add a wait for visible and then a wait for invisible.

    By qdLoaderLocator = By.Id(&quot;line-scale-loader&quot;);
    WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(_driver, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));
    wait.Until(ExpectedConditions.ElementIsVisible(qdLoaderLocator));
    wait.Until(ExpectedConditions.InvisibilityOfElementLocated(qdLoaderLocator));

----

Side note... don&#39;t use Asserts like

    Assert.IsTrue(Elements.SeeException.Count == 0);

because when they fail, you will get

    Expected: true
    Actual: false

which doesn&#39;t tell you anything. Instead use one of the below options.

    Assert.Zero(Elements.SeeException.Count, &quot;Verify no exceptions&quot;);
    Assert.AreEqual(0, Elements.SeeException.Count, &quot;Verify no exceptions&quot;);

Now you will get

    Verify no exceptions
    Expected: 0
    Actual: 2

In this case it might not seem terribly useful but you at least get more information than just true/false. When you start comparing strings, numbers, etc. it will be a LOT more useful.

